==English==

===Etymology===
The origin of the phrase came from when [[chimney sweep]]s were scared to go up the chimneys, the fire would be lit under them in order to motivate them to climb to the top. {{Template:rfv-etymology|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{head|en|verb|head=[[light]] [[a]] [[fire]] [[under]] (someone)}}

# {{context|idiomatic|lang=en}} To [[motivate]] or encourage (someone) to start sooner or move faster.
#: ''Let me see if I can '''light a fire under''' the waiter to get our order sooner.''